Analyzing Data As A Data Scientist & The Body Fat Dataset¶

This lecture will walk through the body fat data set as a data scientist.

Hopefully, this lecture will give a sense of how you, as a data scientist, should approach analyzing data, regardless of the type of analysis you are planning to run.

Body Fat Data¶

The goal of the project is to come up with a simple and accurate way of deteriming body fat percentage of males based on readily available clinical measurements.

The data set contains measurements from 252 men who had their body fat percentage accurately measured via underwater weighing.

  1. The outcome variable is body fat percentage
  2. The set of predictors are every variable except ID number, body fat percentage, and density. In particular, density is not a predictor because body fat was directly calculated based on density (see data description of project 1) and practically speaking, density is not a readily available clinical measurement compared to other predictors in the dataset.

Step 1: Analyzing Raw Data¶

What I typically do first is to look at the raw data to see if there is anything interesting (e.g. precision, units of measurement, outliers, general patterns, etc.)

I also read about any background information related to the data.

Tangent (for your data science career): If the data is too large (i.e. say a million data points), I simply take multiple, small random subset of the original data and examine these subsets.

There are lots of things you can do with plotting and subsetting.

In my opinion, the first two steps help me get a better picture of the data, specifically

  1. How to clean up data (i.e. are some measurements incorrect? )
  2. How measurements are taken (e.g. units, precision, etc.)
  3. Any odd individuals in the data?
  4. General demographic information (e.g. age group, height range, etc.)

Tangent (for your data science career): In real life, you'll spend A LOT of time doing these two steps. Personally, I spend about 70% of my time doing this. If you have a better idea of your data and can clean it at this stage of your data analysis (leaving proper documentation on how you cleaned it), subsequent statistical analysis becomes much easier.

Step 3: Statistical Modeling and Analysis¶

After the first two steps, I try to decide on what type of statistical analysis I want to use.

For this lecture only, we'll look at the relationship between body fat % and age.

What do you see?

Visual questions:

  1. Ordering of the x and y axes?
  2. Units and scaling on y and x axes?
  3. Jittering? Any others?

Statistical questions:

  1. Any dependencies between the two variables, $Y$ and $X$?
  2. Elliptical pattern like the mother-daughter data?
  3. ``Extreme'' points?

Fitting A Simple Linear Regression (SLR) Model¶

$$ \text{ Body Fat Pct }_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{Age}_{i} + \epsilon_i, \quad{} \epsilon_i \sim N(0,\sigma^2) $$

What are the units of the slope and the intercept?

Is the SLR model appropriate for this data?

  1. It is a linear model (i.e. $Y$ is a linear function of the predictors $X$).
  2. The unknown parameters $\beta_0$ and $\beta_1$ are constant (i.e. do not change with $X$).
  3. The error term $\epsilon_i$ is distributed as Normally distributed.
  4. The variance on the error terms is assumed to be constant (i.e. homoskedastic).

There are also several others...can you name them?

In [37]:
plot(AGE,BODYFAT,pch=19,cex=1.2,cex.lab=1.5,cex.main=1.5,
     xlab="Age (yrs)",ylab="Body Fat %",main="Scatterplot of Body Fat % and Age")
lmmodel = lm(BODYFAT ~ AGE)
abline(lmmodel,col="blue",lwd=5) #lwd is the line weight and makes the line thicker.
legend("bottomright",c("SLR Line: slope=0.179,intercept=10.955"),col="blue",lwd=3,lty=c(1))
summary(lmmodel)

According to our SLR model, if we want to use age to predict body fat %, we can use the equation

$$ \text{Body Fat Pct} = 10.955 + 0.179 \text{Age} $$

For example, for a recent male college graduate (e.g. age 22), his predicted body fat % percentage would be around 14.87%. There is a 95% probability that his body fat is between 0.10% and 29.64%.

Observation 1: Age explains about 8.4% of the variation in body fat % (based on $R^2$)

Observation 2: Every year, men gain, on average, 0.179% of body fat %. Every decade, men gain, on average, 1.79% of body fat %.

Testing Relationship Between Age and Body Fat¶

$$ \text{ Body Fat Pct } = 10.955 + 0.179 \text{Age} $$

Suppose the null hypothesis is that age is (linearly) unrelated to body fat %, i.e. $H_0: \beta_1 = 0$, and the alternative is that it isn't, i.e. $H_1: \beta_1 \neq 0$. The associated p-value is 3.04 * 10^-6.

We can declare that there is a linear relationship between age and body fat %. However, our conclusion carries a 5% error rate where we may have falsely declared that there is a relationship even though there truly isn't a relationship.

Correspondingly, the 95% confidence interval for the slope is $(0.10, 0.25)$ and the intercept is $(7.54, 14.37)$. In other words, we are 95% confident that the interval $(0.10, 0.25)$ contains the true slope value $\beta_1$.

Step 4: Diagnostics¶

After model fitting, I typically diagnose the SLR assumptions with a residual plot and a QQ plot.

  1. Residual plot: good for diagnosing (i) linearity vioations, (ii) homoskedasticity violations, and (iii) detecting outliers in $Y$

  2. QQ plot: good for diagnosing violations to Normality

Let's check linearity, homoskedasticity, and Normality.

  2. Homoskedasticity is plausible, but there is a slight > pattern in the residual plot when the predicted body fat is between 20% to 24%.
  3. Normality also looks reasonble because the points in the QQ plot hug the 45 degree line very closely. But, there may be possibly skinny tail or right skew issue (see -2 to 1 region).

Outliers in Y, Leverage and Influential Points¶

For outliers in $Y$, we can use the residual plot above.

From our model of body fat based on age, there also does not seem to be any outliers in $Y$ (this is subjective though...)

  • You'll find that depending on the type of $X$ we use, there may be outliers in $Y$ or leverage/influential points may arise. For example, if we decided that our predictor was weight, then the aforementioned heavy man would probably be a leverage point (or an influential point) and some outliers in $Y$ may arise.

We should also check for leverage and influential points.

For leverage points, we'll use $p_{ii}$ measures from the lectures.

For influential points, we will use both the Cook's distance and the $p_{ii}$ measures.

In [41]:
pii = hatvalues(lmmodel)
cooki = cooks.distance(lmmodel)

     xlab="Index (Each Observation)",ylab="Pii",main="Leverage Values (Pii)")

     xlab="Index (Each Observation)",ylab="Cook's Distance",main="Influence Values (Cook's Distance)")

There may be a leverage point (around the 70th-ish observation).

However, there does not seem to be any influential points by comparing both the Cook's distance and the leverage values.

Our Proposed SLR Model if we want to use age to predict body fat %:

$$ \text{ Body Fat Pct} = 10.955 + 0.179 \text{Age} $$

Possible rule of thumb: "multiply your age by 0.2 and add 11"

A caveat of the rule of thumb is that it tends to underestimate your body fat % compared to the non-rounded estimated model if you are young. It also tends to overestimate your body fat % when you are old. However, this rule of thumb is within the 95% confidence intervals of the slope and the intercept.

Example Usage: for a recent college graduate (e.g. age 22), his predicted body fat % percentage would be around 14.87%. There is a 95% probability that his body fat is between 0.10% and 29.64%. With the rule of thumb, you get about 13.2% as the predicted body fat %.

Inference about Relationship: There is clearly a linear relationship between age and body fat % and this relationship is significant at the $\alpha = 0.05$ level (with p-value $3.04*10^{-6}$). However, age only explains about 8.4% of all the variation in body fat %.

Also, according to this model, every year, a male is expected to gain about 0.18% in body fat %

Strengths and Weakness of Model: I think the SLR is a reasonable model between body fat % and age, despite some caveats.

  1. Linearity: seems reasonable (both based on the residual plot and the original X-Y scatterplot)
  2. Constant effects: probably not reasonable because younger people will have different diets/lifestyle than older people and thus, the slope coefficients may be different for these two subgroups of men
  3. Normally distributed errors: seems plausible from the QQ plot diagnostic (but, possible skinny tailing or right skewing issue)?
  4. Constant variance: This seems plausible, but possible > shape where old people tend to have less variation in their body fat % than young people.
  5. Age only explains 8.4% of the variation in body fat % among men, which is low. Relatedly, the estimate of $\hat{\sigma} \approx 7.435$ (in units of inches), is also high, suggesting a moderately high error variance.

Overall, our model provides a very simple way of guess-timating the body fat % purely based on age. However, because of its simplicity, our predictions aren't very accurate. In addition, when interpreting the linear model, we note that the constant effect assumption is likely vioalted. Other assumptions (linearity, homoskedasticity and Normality) seem plausible, but homoskedasticity and Normality may be slightly violated.
